{{Infobox Australian place | type = protected | name = Broken-Boosey State Park | state = vic | iucn_category = III | image = | caption = | image_alt = | coordinates = {{coord|36|07|51|S|145|33|57|E|display=inline,title}} | relief = 1 | map_alt = | nearest_town_or_city = [[Shepparton, Victoria|Shepparton]] | area = 10.30 | area_footnotes = | established = 2002 | established_footnotes = | visitation_num = | visitation_year = | visitation_footnotes = | managing_authorities = [[Parks Victoria]] | url = http://parkweb.vic.gov.au/explore/parks/broken-boosey-state-park }}
'''Broken-Boosey''' State Park is a linear corridor along sections of Nine Mile Creek, Boosey Creek, and Broken Creek, between [[Shepparton, Victoria|Shepparton]] and [[Tocumwal, New South Wales|Tocumwal]], in [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]]'s north. It covers {{convert|1030|ha|mi2}}, and was declared in 2002.<ref name=pw>[http://parkweb.vic.gov.au/explore/parks/broken-boosey-state-park Broken-Boosey State Park]</ref> It protects some of the few remaining stands of native vegetation in this part of Victoria, including threatened species such as [[coolibah grass]], [[spiny-fruit saltbush]] and [[pepper grass]].<ref name=pw />
