'''Kagome metal''' is a quantum material created in 2018.<ref name=Newsweek>{{citation|title="Kagome metal: new exotic quantum material developed by scientists" |author= Aristos Georgiou |date=March 20, 2018 |work=Newsweek|url=http://www.newsweek.com/kagome-metal-new-exotic-quantum-material-discovered-scientists-853426}}</ref> In the material, metal atoms are arranged in a lattice resembling Japanese ''[[Trihexagonal tiling#Kagome|kagome]]'' basket weaving pattern.<ref>{{citation|title=Japanese basket pattern inspires new material|publisher=BBC|date=20 March 2018|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-43461939}}</ref> The material was announced in ''Nature'' by investigators from [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]], [[Harvard University]] and [[Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory]], all in the United States.<ref name=Newsweek/>
Electrons in the metal experience a "three-dimensional cousin of the [[quantum Hall effect]]".<ref>{{citation|publisher=Massachusetts Institute of Technology|work=MIT News|title=Physicists discover new quantum electronic material|author=Jennifer Chu |date=March 19, 2018|url=http://news.mit.edu/2018/physicists-discover-new-quantum-electronic-material-0319}}</ref>
==See also== *[[Herbertsmithite]], a natural mineral with kagome lattice at the atomic scale *[[Magnon]]
==Further reading== *{{citation|journal=Nature|title=Massive Dirac fermions in a ferromagnetic kagome metal|authors=Linda Ye, Mingu Kang, Junwei Liu, Felix von Cube, Christina R. Wicker, Takehito Suzuki, Chris Jozwiak, Aaron Bostwick, Eli Rotenberg, David C. Bell, Liang Fu, Riccardo Comin & Joseph G. Checkelsky|doi=10.1038/nature25987|date=19 March 2018|arxiv=1709.10007|bibcode=2018Natur.555..638Y}}
