[[File:Snow field near Gibby Beam - geograph.org.uk - 1182123.jpg|thumb|Suncups on a snow patch near Gibby Beam, UK.]]
'''Suncups''' are bowl-shaped open depressions into a [[snow]] surface, normally wider than they are deep. They form closely packed, honeycomb, often hexagonal patterns with sharp narrow ridges separating smoothly concave hollows. For a given set of suncups, the hollows are normally all around the same size, meaning that the [[quasi-periodic|pattern is quasi-periodic]] on 20–80&nbsp;cm scales.<ref name=PostLaChapelle>Post, A., and LaChapelle, E.R. 1971. Glacier ice. Seattle and London, University of Washington Press.</ref><ref name=Herzfeld>Herzfeld, Ute C., et al. "Morphogenesis of typical winter and summer snow surface patterns in a continental alpine environment." Hydrological processes 17.3 (2003): 619-649.</ref> The depressions are typically 2–50&nbsp;cm deep.<ref name=Rhodes>Rhodes, Jonathon J., and Stephen G. Warren. "MODE OF FORMATION OF ABLATION HOLLOWS CONTROLLED BY DIRT CONTENT OF SNOW." ''Journal of Glaciology'' 33.114 (1987).</ref>
Suncups form during the [[ablation]] (melting away) of snowy surfaces. It is thought they can form in a number of different ways. These include melting of clean snow by [[solar gain|incident solar radiation]] in bright [[sunlight|sunny conditions]],<ref name=Rhodes /> but also during melting away of dirty snow under windy or overcast conditions, during which particles in the snow accumulate on the crests between hollows, insulating them.<ref name=Betterton>Betterton, M. D. "Theory of structure formation in snowfields motivated by penitentes, suncups, and dirt cones." Physical Review E 63.5 (2001): 056129.</ref>
==See also== * [[Penitente (snow formation)]], another snow ablation texture
